Europe's passport-free travel zone will be welcoming Croatia.  EU countries today voted on whether or not to admit the three nations into the so-called Schengen zone - a pact between countries to abolish border checks for those travelling between their territories. Croatia received unanimous support from the 26 Schengen member states. If you were using Croatia as a base to reset your Schengen day count you might have to find a different base.  And on the other hand it means more borderless travel for those that have secured a residency or citizenship in Schengen zone.  The world is becoming a smaller place.  #freedomofmovement #borderless #moveabroad #sovereignindividual #sovereigncitizen #croatia #schengencountries #schengenvisa #digitalnomad #nomadlife

Working as a digital nomad in Antigua and Barbuda has the following benefits: â€¢Easy internet access. With an internet speed fixed 20.95 Mbps and mobile 33.80 Mbps, you can work in any part of the world from Antigua & Barbuda, feeling at home or office. â€¢Smooth visa application process. Applying for the Antigua & Barbuda digital nomad visa is fairly easy, and everything is done online. Moreover, you will have to wait only 14 days for an answer. â€¢Tax exemption. As a digital nomad, you are exempt from ping income taxes in Antigua and Barbuda. â€¢Warm climate. With a tropical savannah climate, Antigua & Barbuda has pleasing year-round weather. The best time to visit Antigua & Barbuda is November to April, when it is least rainy and hot. â€¢Delicious cuisine. Antigua & Barbuda has become a food destination because of its fresh seafood, flavored dishes, and top-notch rum. This place is a haven for rum distilleries and sugar plantations. â€¢Leisure activities. In Antigua & Barbuda, you can enjoy a variety of activities. Among the activities you can enjoy are exploring rainforests, swimming with stingrays, biking, kayaking, diving, snorkeling, sailing, and fishing. Michael and Acacia (yeti.the.van) have been living full-time in "Yeti the Van" for over a year now. They're both originally from South Africa and have spent the majority of their first year in Yeti exploring their own country and region.  In this video, Michael and Acacia want to share a little bit about their story and why they chose to live full-time in a van.  In May 2021 they started their nomadic journey living in a small Suzuki SUV. This move was done for them to begin exploring and traveling but also for them to start saving up to be able to afford Yeti.  Michael and Acacia are professional videographers and photographers and find that their nomadic lifestyle has allowed their business to expand.  This video was brought to you by Orion by Up-Switch. It is a fully integrated Nintendo Switch Portable HD 11.6 inch IPS Monitor which is perfect for gaming on the road. It was a flat fee of $2.00 to see the doctor and he prescribed us a natural remedy to break her fever which cost $3.00 So basically,  $5.00 and 45 minutes later we were back at home taking care of the baby. People always tell me how they want to travel like me or have my life, and I have two things to say to that: 1. My life isn't all that you see on social media. There's a lot (both good and bad) that I don't post here. I have my issues, just like anyone else. But perhaps most importantly, I don't travel as much as it looks like on social media. Don't get me wrong, I travel a lot, but as an aspiring content creator I have to post travel content on a daily basis, several times a day, across multiple platforms. I can assure you I don't travel every day, or every week or every month. 2. Everyone comes from a different background and I've been very lucky when it comes to travel. I'm not going to sit here and deny my priviledge.  That said, no one handed this life to me. The content creation, solo travel and potentially being a full-time traveler, that was all me. It all started with a decision to change the way I lived and take risks in order to pursue what I wanted. And more importantly, action followed that decision. That is the most important thing. #travellife #travellifestyle #travellifeâœˆï¸ #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #digitalnomadtravel

The digital nomad Visa is the perfect  Way to see and live in another country if you have a job that is remote or if you work for yourself. These countries will let you live there as long as you can prove that you make a certain income which most of the time is their minimum wage. Here are all the countries that I mentioned,  Norway Bahamas Portugal Germany  Barbados Greece Iceland Romania  Indonesia Italy Spain Taiwan and Mexico.  I also mentioned Australia New Zealand Ireland South Korea and Singapore do not have this program but will let you stay there for a year with a  working holiday Visa which I can talk about in another video.  As a full time traveler and digital nomad and backpacker these are some of the best tools to use to see the world for cheap, it is also a great alternative to the gap year. Replying to @lisaserota  Here are all my budget travel tips and travel recommendations for someone going to visit Tokyo, Japan.  1st I would recommend  Going to all the different cities within Tokyo, Japan such as shinjuku shibuya asakusa rapungi and so on.  Then I would also recommend going to Tokyo Disneyland and sea, the studio ghibli museum, the Ramen museum, TeamLABS Tokyo and some of the more popular places like Sensoji temple, Tokyo sky tree, Tsukiji fish market, and the Imperial palace.  As for food I would recommend trying yakaniku and ramen as well as my favorite Japanese chicken Katsu curry, CoCo Ichibanya is great quick and easy for katsu curry but I may also recommend somewhere that isn't a chain that specializes in katsu curry. Additionally, I would also recommend going outside of the city to Fuji, Kyoto, Osaka and Himeji with the JR Rail pass. #tokyotravel #visittokyo #budgettraveller #budgettraveltips #fulltimetravel #fulltimetraveller #digitalnomads #japantraveltips #visitjapan #digitalnomadlifestyle

slow travel isn't always necessarily to do with time. it's true that we don't always have the opportunity to spend a few weeks or months in one place, but even still, we can slow down our pace.  avoid trying to squeeze everywhere and everything in, making a checklist of must do's and a plan to see them back to back, let go of spending time in the popular places that actually don't make your soul light up and release any feelings of guilt that may come with believing that you're seeing less. by doing this, you'll come away with actually experiencing more. go on long walks without a set direction, stopping at whichever place, restaurant or cafe that 'just feels good,' to you, be open to long conversations with strangers, and spend some leisurely time watching the world go by and soaking it all in. by all means, have a little pre-list of highlights you'd love to see, but stay open to the flow and the beauty that comes with going slow. ğŸ“aix en provence . . . . . #madeformore #createyourdreamlife #madetottravel #freedomlifestyle #freedomlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #slowtravel #slowtraveller #slowtravelling #lifejourney #authenticexperience #localfinds #localtips #freespirit #fulltimetraveller #womentravelsolo #solofemaletravel #solofemaletraveler #solofemaletraveller #provence #provencelife #aixenprovence

Full time travel does not equal a vacation. It is easy to see full time travelers and digital nomads as well as people on gap years as taking just extended vacations these long elaborate trips where they are staying in nice places they are doing all of the touristy things and seeing the sites. What's important to know is that most of the time that is not the case, people that travel full time do so mostly because they are either already working still and are retaining a full time remote job or a part time remote job that funds this experience, or they are potentially working at the places they're traveling like working for the hostel or for a ski resort, or they've saved a lot of money, sometimes over the course of years to be able to afford the travel they are currently doing. Still though the truth of the matter is that when you are traveling full time unless you use credit card  Sign on bonuses and are travel hacking like I am most of the experiences that you are having are staying in hostels for extremely cheap not paying for expensive hotels like many would on vacation, they may have quit comfy jobs at home and are just living life. It is no longer a vacation it is your life, and that is why people traveling full time aren't spending as much every day because they're not as rushed to see absolutely everything in every place they have the time to take it slow, Eat at street food vendors instead of nice restaurants, take the free walking tours instead of the one's Trip Advisor recommends for a couple $100 And focus on local experiences rather than catered experiences to tourism. Full time travel is about the experiences and feeling the place in its most authentic way not about seeing everything that you can and spending all of your money.  That's my take anyway let me know what you think? And if you want to know how to full time travel as well then follow along and I'll tell you how!  #digitalnomad #digitalnomadlife #digitalnomadlifestyle #fulltimetraveler #fulltimetravel #travelforcheap #gapyear #gapyeartravel #vacationtips #travelfulltime

Ditch the heavy luggage! - I found that packing light is a MUST when you plan to move around from place to place in a short period of time.  Starting in Europe, the buildings are much older and you might find yourself staying on the 3rd or 4th floor with no elevator through multiple cities. Carrying that 50lb hard side will get exhausting even when just trying to pull it along the old stone roads. Once you get comfortable you wonâ€™t wear most of what you bring anyhow so PACK LIGHT, trust me ğŸ™ğŸ¾ 2. It might get lonely - Youâ€™re solo-traveling so of course you know youâ€™re going to be alone, but feeling lonely is a totally different thing to prepare for.  Itâ€™s bound to happen especially if you visit smaller cities where some of the popular apps to meet people arenâ€™t as widely used.  I found that booking a tour of the city or food tour can be a great way to meet others and help feel less alone on your trip.  Also, just getting outside and being around the locals by working at a cafe or having a drink a bar can get you out of a rut if you find yourself in one.  These are just a couple things Iâ€™ve learned so far.  Iâ€™ll continue to share more tips as I continue to travel ğŸ‘¨ğŸ¾â€ğŸ’» What questions do you have about the nomad life or solo-traveling ? [Freelancing Life] Besides doing a 9 to 5 job, I also have some freelance jobs as my additional income. Doing a freelance job while also having a full-time job mengharuskan saya untuk mengorbankan beberapa hal, seperti waktu tidur yang akhirnya lebih sedikit, waktu weekend, dan kesenangan masa muda lainnya. Beberapa minggu ini saya coba mengubah pola kerja saya, dari yang sebelummya kerja sampai larut setelah selesai full-time, menjadi kerja lebih pagi sebelum full-time. I try to sleep as early as possible setelah selesai kerjaan full-time, kemudian bangun lebih pagi untuk ngerjain side project or freelance job. Tantangan untuk terus belajar hal baru seringkali datang dari freelance job and for me this is my chance to sharpen my skills. For me, selagi masih muda, selagi energi nya masih banyak dan otak nya masih kuat untuk belajar hal-hal baru, mengorbankan kesenangan-kesenangan jangka pendek bukanlah hal yang perlu disesali.
